    "constituents_description": "The most important healing constituents of Rubus londinensis are ellagic acid, quercetin, anthocyanins, kaempferol, and gallic acid, which have been identified as key bioactive compounds responsible for its medicinal properties. Ellagic acid exhibits antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, and anticancer activities, while quercetin has been shown to inhibit histamine release, platelet aggregation, and oxidative stress. Anthocyanins, responsible for the fruit's red color, have antioxidant properties and may help mitigate cardiovascular disease by reducing inflammation and improving vascular function. Kaempferol, a flavonoid with anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties, may help protect against neurodegenerative diseases and cancer. Gallic acid has been shown to exhibit antimicrobial, antioxidant, and anti-inflammatory activities, which contribute to the plant's wound-healing, anti-inflammatory, and antimicrobial properties.",
